Duel on Messer Schneide: MP3 player against mobile phones.
We advise you on your choice
While almost any mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can still phone.
So, of course, it looks like it’s better to just buy a phone.
After all, there are plenty of reasons why you should buy a standalone player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the claims of the future owners.
Surely you can hardly buy a great expensive record player at home to listen to the latest album by Maxim Turbulenc.
Once such musical novelties do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view, there is no objective reason for this either.
However, if you have LPs with art rock, jazz or blues on the shelf, you probably dream of at least one.
This is also the case with music on the go, that is, with compressed music, in simple terms - music in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For one, it may not be acceptable to spend eighteen thousand crowns for a player, but a Pink-Floyd fan will probably hardly get headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide-ranging.
The life of the batteries is also crucial.
Some good music players can play much more than just music, but what mobile phones can do, they don’t even make a hint.
No modern device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, calling and simsing, it can play music and videos, record both, it has a better one, a worse camera, and maybe also can navigate.
And if you include the smartphones and communicators, you have almost a small computer in your pocket.
It’s a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV can photograph.
But the universality of mobile phones also has disadvantages.
However, the more features you use on your phone, the more often you will need to reload it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few phones can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this respect, Music Players (especially the simplest) are significantly more powerful.
That’s why you should expect cheap phones that they won’t be able to play music for more than a few hours.
If you still make calls from time to time, you’d better buy an office charger for safety – this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you will not have this problem, even the less good ones will last at least 9 hours of continuous operation with one time charging out.
Another problem is when you want to overplay the music on your phone.
Unfortunately, only a small part of the devices has a USB connector, and not every phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, you can overplay the music directly to a storage medium, but only a few card readers can be done without reduction with the tiny memory cards used in mobile phones.
Players do not require special software except for exceptions (iPod).
You only need to feed the device via USB port with music from your PC.
Most phones and players create a music library themselves, sorted by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the genre or, for example, the user rating.
Some devices only represent the tree structure of the address book, similar to the Windows Explorer, some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones can do more
When choosing a specific device, you should inquire especially about the battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound, and of course also the ease of operation.
Is music especially for you, and you listen to it every day just briefly, for example, in the tram, then any phone that plays MP3 files is enough.
This is something that almost any phone can do.
You also don’t have to control which music formats a phone or player can process.
MP3 create all, and most of the music you get will be just in this format.
The format is one of the most widely used, and most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format that Apple and its iPods use).
Better mobile phones also make it possible to buy music online.
You only need to access the corresponding pages of a provider (or another provider) via mobile internet, and you can already buy a song or album.
This service can be a striking argument for why you should buy a music phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of the providers is poor and is usually limited to fast radio hits.
The prices are not the lowest either.
In general, however, it is assumed that this type of music sales (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry the phone with them.
If you want to listen to something, grab the phone in your jacket pocket while the player is lying at home.
However, it depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least a wireless hands-free device.
If not, you can resort to the built-in speaker that almost every phone has, but only the fewest MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music phones will be in the price for many.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
For three and four thousand crowns you already get a decent walkman.
The biggest handicap for most people will be that there are no normal headphones.
The best and most technically mature phones with a 3.5mm aperture for normal headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the players in turn lies in the ease of operation.
The simplest - and not necessarily the cheapest (see selection) - player can really serve anyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity in operation with the previously normal cassette recorder or, for example, the record player is obvious.
There is no threat of collision in the form of an erroneously employed mobile internet and a subsequent horrific bill for data transmissions.
Which device should you use now
