Even if you buy a suitable card, two thousand crowns will suffice.
But be careful.
For the basic models, as a rule, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported.
Only the most expensive ones can read 8GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, then go to Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you will not need to put more than 1100 crowns on the table.
Be among the more demanding listeners, prefer to take specialized phones - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have independent control buttons for MP3, and the ease of use is similar to that of a single MP3 player.
The most widespread here is Sony Ericsson, whose phones from the Walkman series have the same user interface as the individually sold MP3 players.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand kroner, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours) will allow you MP3 players from the above-mentioned manufacturers.
The first virtual provider is coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Might be.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, there is something missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classics to lower prices.
Maybe this one won't be waiting for long.
The fact that Czech mobile operators are among the most expensive in Europe has been reported on Mobil.cz many times.
By the way, this was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which pointed out that the price for a SMS here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the latest steps of the European Commission in the area of regulation of roaming fees, there is so likely to be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are prices so high in the Czech Republic compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a statement of battle.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, because in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
The mobile operators, on the other hand, like to scoff at the fact that there is extremely much competition in the Czech market.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has often stated in the past that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic, often owes this.
It’s probably true that a classic provider with their own network doesn’t have a lot of chances anymore (by the way, they probably wouldn’t even find frequencies anymore).
But there is another option - a virtual provider.
It was precisely the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market that led to a significant price reduction, to which the classic mobile operators had to react.
Even before companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market in the UK, there were similar voices as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
You don’t have to look for examples for a long time.
In February we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to attract more than 100 thousand customers and thus become the country’s fifth largest provider.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to work effectively, virtual vendors need far fewer customers than a classic vendor.
They do not require relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost companies – they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, but this is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to bet on a non-clic target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
“Real guys choose Mobilking – the provider they like and trust,” said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could also take hold in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offer."
In the Czech Republic, the mobile operators say
But it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
Mobilking is more likely to enter the market in other countries in our region,” Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, told Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competitor arises.
Her interest in launching a virtual mobile provider has long been demonstrated by the GTS Novera Group, which wants to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the corporate customer sector.
"We have a great interest in providing our customers not only fixed network but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already been able to make progress in negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
Maybe better times are coming.
Unofficial information suggests that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this has been surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
“At the moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from Telefónica O2's press department in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other providers also point to the specifics of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with O2's statement: "Until now, we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build."
And she adds: “T-Mobile’s network will hardly have a virtual provider by the end of the year.
At this point, we should already have a concrete offer in order to be able to think so short-term."
Vodafone is focusing more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we see as the best from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
The responsible authorities - with the providers in hand
The actions of the mobile operators are easy to understand, another provider would mean more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
So why should it be easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull on a string when it comes to something is also evidenced by the long run around the creation of U:fon.
The strongest pressure towards <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was exerted by T-Mobile when U:fon entered the market.
This is also evidenced by publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
But now U:fon is suitable as an argument for why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment in the mobile telecom market has recently been strengthened by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile telecom provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services."
However, in view of this approach of the mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulators is surprising.
This is not only the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which unfortunately - unlike the United Kingdom and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It is owned exclusively by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, referred to his very typical attitude to the whole problem.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile operator would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile operator and a virtual provider on the leasing of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not interesting enough for the classic providers," said Kristián Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS in his reply to our inquiry.
Representatives of the providers would not be surprised by such a formulation.
This is more than suspicious of an authority that represents the interests of consumers and, among other things, is to ensure that no one abuses its position in the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In a foreign country where virtual providers work quite normally, it can be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile phone services."
However, it is likely that pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are not in the interests of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
What is really shocking in this case is the almost touching harmony of the three mobile providers, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just like the absolutely identical gasoline price at the gas stations, it is certainly just a coincidence and the result of a tough competition.
"The Authority has not found in this case any indication of anti-competitive action and therefore has no reason to intervene in the matter in any way.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions in the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market to virtual providers are probably lacking in the regulatory authority for telecommunications," Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, developed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, after telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators holds a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different perspective - for a virtual provider to enter the market, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile provider has, logically, the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a certain segment.
However, even if you do not agree with this argument, it should at least be a warning to the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators are strikingly similar.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
In the telecommunications services, the devolution of responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is then a fairly common trick, with which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recently adopted novelty of the Telecommunications Act, the extension of the competences of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> to the field of economic competition in telecommunications has not succeeded, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS need to know this too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's okay when no one's looking
First of all, the functioning of any pseudo-virtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partially public.
Usually, these are companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Own mobile phone services include Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the selected ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar type of resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual terms that we will then deal with, which can lead to a termination of cooperation with the respective company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not be talked about by the responsible mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, they can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such a procedure.
In fact, the activity of these companies generates non-negligible profits, while at the same time - unlike the actual virtual providers - they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite all, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it like the normal customers of the mobile carriers."
That alone, however, should at least seem strange to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, another question opens up for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Do the mobile providers close their eyes to such a procedure, why do they block themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has quite strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the declaration of the providers, they would not know about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As the text has already stressed on several occasions, the entry of virtual providers into the market led to a significant price decline in the various services.
In virtually all countries where virtual providers have emerged, traditional providers have tried to prevent their emergence practically more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market that was too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, it was precisely in these moments that the regulators intervened, which in no way tried to safeguard the interests of the mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and this was followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in the competences in these cases is more than favorable.
But we don't throw the shotgun into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon be back in motion.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile provider, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And then the Czechs will finally not phone more expensive than the rest of Europe.
