The Prague transport companies will also transport a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will enter the history of Prague’s transport companies as a date on which the first passengers to enter a subway, tram or bus will carry an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
Currently, about one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card can buy them.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and have it recorded on their chip card at the information centres and branch offices of the transport companies at the metro stations Muzeum, M<0xC5><0xAF>stek, Nádra<0xC5><0xBE>í Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice, Koby<0xC5><0x88>ky, And<0xC4><0x9B>l, Rozty<0xC4><0x8D>e.
The coupons have also been available on the Internet since yesterday on the pages of the transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by over four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use internet sales can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they have had to wait regularly in long queues for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon via the Internet, it is played on the opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these points, travelers also have a desk with trained staff that advises interested parties when buying online and also records the coupon on the map," said Martin Opatrn<0xC3><0xBD>, spokesman for the project.
