Rats also have feelings.
Does a rat or a cockroach flee in danger mean that it also feels fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
Just how could you check if they feel the same if they behave similarly to us?
For several years, the Internet magazine "Edge" has been publishing articles by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove this so far where we can’t even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we should at least hope, since all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and cut questions of sensation or of consciousness in general, we enter rugged terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it becomes dead, flees or attacks.
Humans behave similarly, which some scientists conclude is a comparable subjective experience.
But I don't believe in that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and execution/control functions).
This broad region is much higher developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowing who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is therefore reason to assume that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of man: since so much of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness does not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, whatever it may be, is likely to be very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it cannot be measured or, because of the special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then his research poses us with great problems.
Most of my presentations relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that should be more scientifically accessible.
One could examine the consciousness processes of animals without regard to their contents, and this is exactly what happens in studies on the short-term memory of primates, particularly in the example of visualization.
But with this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick pursued, one relies more on the neural correlates of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the emergence of visualization.
What happens to the sensations?
I lead them back to the fact that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in one of its own activity-conscious brains.
So what we call “fear” is the mental state in which we are when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies memory.
In this way, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and, in particular, humans.
Associated with the linguistic nature, there are fine gradations of sensation, because with the help of words and grammar we can differentiate and categorize states in order to attribute them to others besides ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio believes, for example, that sensations from more primitive activities in the body-emotion regions of the cortex and brain stem are similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it may well be involved in cross-genre sensations.
Theoretically, I can’t deny it, but I think it’s unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in rats and humans probably feels the same way in both cases: But how can you check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
A cockroach flees when in danger, even if she feels fear?
In my eyes, mere similarity of behavior cannot yet prove similarity of experience.
While the neural comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain stems, cockroaches, on the other hand, do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove it to humans, how would you prove it to rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have sensations.
But I didn't know how to prove it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior rather than the emotional feelings of rats.
In any case, progress on the neural level is signaled here, provided that the same is measured in rats and humans.
Just as I do not study language and consciousness in rats, nor do I explore sensations, I do not know if they exist.
You may think of it as short-sighted, but I prefer to move forward rather than constantly running against a wall.
I am a practical emotionalist.
