Debate on bilingual education: education in an English-speaking environment
In this issue of "Education Watch", Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of the candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, Senior Research Fellow in California Studies and Senior Director of Educational Sciences at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book “Not As Good As You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs a School Choice.”
Addressing Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barack Obama’s proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama’s election campaign mentions that “the likelihood of African-American and Hispanic students successfully completing school is lower than that of white students” — which is true.
To close this gap in performance, Obama’s education plan specifically recommends, among other things, a bilingual transitional phase in education for those who are learning English first.
Nevertheless, the question to Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the gap in school benefits.
Take for example "Sixth Street Prep", an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than one-third of students, many of whom have recently been in the country, are learning English.
Nevertheless, in 2008, an astonishing 100 percent of fourth graders passed the state exam in mathematics at a good level.
Surprisingly, 93% of the children from the fourth year of school were rated as good in the English exam.
This astonishing success was achieved by methods other than those preferred by Obama.
The Sixth Street School places its emphasis on review and practice, on constant control of knowledge and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
In addition, the school is practicing the approach followed by education in an English-speaking environment, which is exactly the point that Obama should pay attention to, according to the head of the school Linda Mikels.
This approach emphasizes the almost exclusive use of the English language in professional teaching.
Ms. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school would have been a remarkable success with a student who had just come from Mexico. 12 months later, you would be able to enter the classroom and not recognize him anymore.
“It works,” she noted, “it works for us.”
Would Obama take a school like the “Sixth Street Prep” as a model for other schools with a large proportion of Latin American and other English-learning students?
The school’s achievements would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational policy positions within its own party (the national non-formal associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and its own consistent support for bilingual education make predictions about Obama’s response uncertain.
While he agrees with the point that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about the “English-only” legislation.
Instead, he said, “You should make sure that your child can speak Spanish.”
If Obama really wants to close the gap in performance, he should carefully consider educational models that work, rather than despise and trivialize them.
