The oil price fell sharply on Monday due to fears that even the U.S. bailout plan for the financial markets might not be enough to revive the economy.
The crude oil futures trades on the New York Stock Exchange fell 7% in the morning session to $99.80 per barrel.
Since last Monday, the price has fallen by more than $20.
In the past two weeks, commodity markets have been shaken by both financial turmoil on Wall Street and violent storms in the Gulf of Mexico.
After prices peaked at $145.29 per barrel in July, they have fallen to almost $90 per barrel this month, and then rise again as a result of the enormous uncertainty in financial markets.
Investors have already shown concern again on Monday, despite congressional officials announcing they had agreed on a bailout plan over the weekend, which should be the largest in history.
This news was overshadowed by new concerns that the financial crisis is far from over.
In the penultimate chapter of the growing crisis, according to a government announcement on Monday, Citigroup is to buy the banking operations of the Wachovia Corporation.
In the meantime, the Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments have partially nationalised the European financial group Fortis.
According to analysts at Barclays Capital, despite the tense negotiations that took place over the weekend and led to a bailout plan, it has apparently failed to revive the mood in the markets.
As the economic situation continues to deteriorate, demand for goods, including oil, is expected to continue to decline.
Analysts at Deutsche Bank have written in a message to investors that forecasts for global capital markets, interest rates and exchange rates have become extremely uncertain.
We believe, they continue to write, that the commodity markets will also be affected.
“From a commodity market perspective, we are most concerned about whether the U.S. virus is spreading worldwide, especially to China.”
Analysts at the bank have adjusted their expectations for oil consumption downwards due to weak economic growth for the coming year, and lowered their forecasts for oil and gas prices for 2009 by 20%.
