The pride and the hardships in the life of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Hidden among the hustle and bustle of the amusement parks around Orlando, a few miles away from the glittering, loud and gigantic hustle and bustle, lies a quiet city where the pride and complications of African-American culture emerge.
Eatonville, the first entirely black city in the country and the home town of Zora Neale Hurstons, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquet pitches, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Nowadays it is a pilgrimage site.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet the city that describes it – and that made it a tourist destination by including it in the Florida travel guide produced by the Federal Writers’ Project during the depression – is in many ways a place of a very special sort.
Eatonville is as independent, prosperous, and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he's missing."
Even today, in a year in which a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open conversation about racial relations, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
"We are very concerned about how our story is told," said Hortense Jones, 59, from birth to a city dweller and community member of the city's oldest church.
It has to be voted."
Eatonville has long been defined as the paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of nearly 2,400 inhabitants, in which the poverty rate is twice as high as the country’s average.
It is, on the one hand, a fortress of literature and, on the other, an example of the – sometimes condemned, sometimes praised – black culture of the rural south, which has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and on guard.
And so rightly did the concerns about Eatonville's image actually begin with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She presented her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in oral form, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1973)
Five paragraphs in the Florida Travel Guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that leads through Florida’s often-forgotten center, to the scenes of black history and human drama.
Naughty as Oskar in both real life and literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Away from the road to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-and-white-painted modern school, with its well-kept gardens and playgrounds, which Howard Miller always cares about, although he can barely read and write."
She also mentioned the new husband of Widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and what-always-fits-hour rooms."
Thus, in just a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by everyone.
“Zora described things as they were,” said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson’s girls, who immortalized Hurston by quoting the men who sang songs about her beauty that were full of sexual hints.
She added: "Some people don't like this."
Hurtson is still remembered as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston came brewed in the city, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and dressed in pants, in a city that even today imagines something on her venerable clothing style.
According to Mr. Franklin, most residents were fascinated, while many despised them.
"People were always happy to see Zora," Mr. Franklin said.
But “she never stayed too long,” he added as he swinged in his chair, on a rear-facing terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, in which Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were stolen.
Together with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous tomb in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville there was no great commemoration, no public readings in the grand style.
“I don’t think they understood their contribution to the world or their heritage at all,” said Valerie Boyd, author of Wrapped in Rainbows, a 2003 biography about Hurston.
The turn came in the 80s.
Orange County authorities wanted to lay a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the municipality's slow two-lane main road.
Orlando’s suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult phase in his history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred into the community.
"At this time, a bunch of white boys often came and they threw oranges and stuff at the people sitting out," Franklin said.
“There was even a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In 1955, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's demand to enforce integration, calling its decision in the Brown case against the school council "offensive rather than respectful of my race."
Residents today say that although the abolition of racial segregation was positive in some ways, it weakened the group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
“Black children were used to being hugged—I remember—you hugged your teacher in the morning and you hugged your teacher in the evening,” said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and managing director of the nonprofit group to protect the Eatonville community.
This could be sustained so long, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"You didn't embrace your white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there's a cultural divide," Nathiri said.
However, civil rights have helped make room for more Zora Neale Hurstons – black authors, actors, and artists who pushed themselves beyond prejudice, as she did, with positive self-confidence and statements like, “How can anyone deny the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker set out on her way to Hurston's nameless grave and began to fight for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a much-loved Hurston biography of Robert E. Hemenway was found in the bookshelves, making it once again part of the American literary canon.
The long-distance project came exactly at a time when Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The municipality began planning a Hurston festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
"The plans for a five-lane highway animated the city, accelerated the whole thing at peak speed, aroused real civic pride," Nathiri said.
Ms. Boyd put it a little easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the long-distance project has contributed to a change in the city’s self-image.
More and more train travelers came, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to re-evaluate the past.
Eatonville was inscribed on the nationwide historical register in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville is still a specialty in Florida: just 6 miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a backstreet in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(She is 90% black nowadays.)
Outsiders looking for the history of Eatonville and its significance are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, prior approval is necessary and certain things – such as the mural of Eatonville’s oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men in the field – are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Ms. Jones, a courageous, self-confident teacher with a preference for dark red, still fear that their shielded community is misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival grew, an increased degree of home pride was also born.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw their entire race: beautiful, with all his problems, neither worse nor better, and as proud, creative and hardworking, silly and mixed as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city administration or the police, which he believes may need some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to correctly describe Eatonville.
"Most people who just drive through here will think, 'Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,'" Kenon said on a Sunday after the church.
“But if you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it’s a very beautiful city.”
