Conversation - From the Blood That Became Safe Again
Hema-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
Above all, it has regained public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross blood donation service were infected with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public dissatisfaction, the Government of Canada launched in February 1994 a public investigation, led by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at bringing light to the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and drawing up guidelines to prevent a recurrence of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to submit his report, several provinces at the time set up a committee to develop a new system for managing blood cans in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this task.
According to reports by Gélineau and Cancer, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Company, to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Quebec took up her work, hardly 38% of people had confidence in the blood-conserving system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was daunting.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood cans and through work in this area over the next few years, we have regained public confidence,” she says, before proudly stressing that by early 2008, almost 94% of Quebec’s population had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that ‘trust is something extremely fragile’.
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has acted on the principle of caution.
At that time, we experienced the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of bovine insanity in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says this woman, who has been in charge since its inception in 1998.
And we had no idea if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we referred to one of the main guidelines of the reports by Krebs and Gélineau, according to which exclusion measures are applied if you do not know this and if a disease only progresses slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is manifested by a degeneration of the brain, which is unweigering to.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, it was undoubtedly proven that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied makes sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NSTs), which enable the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in the donor’s blood, rather than the antibody against the virus, as was the case with the tests used previously.
The NSTs made it possible to shorten the incubation time that occurs between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize this, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting blood infected with HIV.
In other words, you have to distribute 12 million cans of blood before someone gets HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 cans of blood each year, it would take more than 24 years for a case to occur in which HIV was transmitted via a can of blood.
I believe that it is possible to feel comfortable nowadays when you receive a blood transfusion or prescribe it to restore health," says the head of Hema-Quebec.
“Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can get into the system.
Only last year did the Chikungunya virus appear on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted through the blood by insects.
We need to monitor uninterruptedly,” Dr. Décary continues, before stressing that Hema-Québec must also provide adequate care in addition to a safe supply.
“Demand is increasing because the population is ageing.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donation network, which averages only 3% of Quebec’s eligible residents.
Every healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the fitness criteria can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who make their blood available are not accepted because, for example, they have AIDS or malaria, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria is prevalent are excluded from donating blood for a year.
With this 3%, we manage to get an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all, to keep them and make them become regular donors.
Life is so hectic nowadays that you rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec delivers not only canned blood, but also human tissue, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is used almost exclusively for severe burn injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec’s only public umbilical cord blood bank.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, there is blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
A few weeks ago, we celebrated the storage of our thousandth cord blood sample, and we plan to lose more than a thousand per year.
"We should probably start making it available for transplants early next year," explains Dr. Décary, who describes this umbilical cord blood collection program as very popular.
“Many mothers are convinced they don’t have access to it because Hema-Quebec lacks the resources to offer this complex and costly program in all hospitals in Quebec.
