Free Opinion - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Deputy Director General of the Canadian Gold Mine Barrick Gold.
This confirms, and follows an Orwellian logic, that the world’s largest gold mining company sought a slanderous lawsuit of over six million against three authors and a small, medium-sized publishing house with the aim of opening a ‘public transparent debate’.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge about the truth, especially not in the case of libel complaints, but about the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to represent one of their opposing opinions.
No matter how the process turns out, the authors and publishers of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid out of the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactics in these unequal struggles are, by the way, often to ruin the defenders in order to enforce a consensual arrangement that mutates the opposite side and also deters anyone who dares to deal with the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her view of things to the public.
In contrast to what is commonplace in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually carried out through the exchange of ideas and not by leaps and bounds.
So it would have been enough if the gold mine had exposed its books and files and opened a real debate through which newspapers, media, publications and the funding of independent testing teams could have brought light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to have confidence in public opinion and wipes out the petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada with a hand movement.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how he could at the same time ask for a 'public' debate, while disregarding the opinions of this public?
Apparently, in the world of the Vice-President, this word includes only the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a very narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does this primarily because it rejects the brutal stance of the gold mine.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a snag (in the course of the 'public debate' Barrick Gold has just addressed a demand to the authors of Noir Canada in which she no longer demands to use these).
Apart from Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom to academic research and the discovery of truth that are fundamental to any democratic society.
It utterly denies the right to cite credible sources and discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to explore and discuss issues that the rich companies of this world do not like, who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could lead it by following the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to handle debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate, and it is time for governments to take measures to limit this kind of unjustified complaint.
