The Psychology of Overdoing – Or Why We Are Ready to Pay More
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overestimate the wrong bid.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological and economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in "Science" magazine, people in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, do not want to be beaten and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play the lottery while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases, the subjects' active brain regions were examined by functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to earn money, however, increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cerebral cortex, was measured in losers of the auction, in which overcoming the opponent plays an essential role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have also conducted research to trace the money.
In this case, three groups should participate against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their contributions.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward in case they emerge as winners of the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was only that the emphasis on one was on winning while the other was on losing.
However, as proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the “against losing” group were willing to bet higher than those in the control or “winning” group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
This is because the behaviors observed at auctions so far have only been motivated by the joy of winning, or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved thanks to imaging neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation ready," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should I see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected is estimated to be one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is due to the fact that patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - inflammation of the liver and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, vaginal secretions or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B, but there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain, and vomiting.
After that, jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes light, the urine darkens, and recovery can take up to two to three weeks.
Approximately 1 million people worldwide die each year from hepatitis B, far more serious diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis of the liver.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people is in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed people.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease can already be detected during a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult a GP at the first signs of unknown origin.
Timely detected, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby banishing the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30th is World Hepatitis Day, held in 2004 for the first time by patient representations worldwide.
The aim of the action is to raise awareness of this chronic inflammation caused by viruses, its occurrence and the importance of early detection.
