Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment: it was investigated to what extent faith in God affects human pain, reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electroshock while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the believers were able to eliminate most of the pain.
Using brain scan technology, it was even proven that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for pain regulation.
The study was the first in a research project in which, in addition to scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university also participate.
During the experiment, the subjects were connected to a sparkling device on the left hand, which gave the electroshocks.
Participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: on the one hand a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other hand Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with the Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke some sort of religious trance among the faithful, while choosing da Vinci’s painting, because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt reassuring.
The subjects spent half an hour each in an MRI scanner, and received a total of 20 electroshocks in four stages during this time, while viewing either the religious or the other paintings.
The Catholics reported that they felt “safe” at the sight of the Mother of God, as if they were “concerned” and felt “peace and quiet.”
While viewing the religious painting, they reported about 12% less pain than if they had Leonardo’s work in mind.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thought that similar effects could also be produced with other, strong-acting images, even among the atheists, you just had to find the corresponding photo.
"We would have to find an image that triggers very positive feelings, such as a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
“Practicing faith should change our personality, and it does so in many cases,” Wright said.
After these excellent results, only the question remains, what effect would a Madonna picture of Leonardo or another similar painter have on the pain regulation of the faithful.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On the occasion of her tenth birthday, Google can rightly claim that she is found in people’s pockets as well as above their heads in the sky: she knows where people have spent their holidays, what specialists they go to, and what moves them.
And that’s still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of Google’s CEOs.
Towards skeptics plagued by Orwellian horror visions, he makes it clear that they would overlook just the essence of Web 2.0.
In an interview with the Financial Times, Schmidt recently said that Google’s main goal is to collect even more personal data about users and thus get closer to the company’s original goal of “ordering all the information in this world.”
Schmidt said Google was still at the beginning of information gathering after ten years of world-changing work.
Asked about the status quo in five years, Schmidt said he wished Google would be able to answer questions like “What should I do tomorrow?” or “What job really suits me?”, but software programs are still unable to do so because they don’t know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that in the course of their Internet searches the search terms would be registered, as well as the IP addresses from which they were searched and the pages visited.
For example, the "Personalized Search" introduced two years ago allows the visitor to save their own search history and later resort to it, so that the hits can be generated much more accurately later, and on the same logic are also based the so-called "recommendations", with which the system receives customized products and services based on the previous.
However, users are wondering what happens in the event of a data abuse – “when you look at what I do” – some are concerned about Google’s data monopoly.
In most cases, however, it is rather the potential power represented by the company that is arousing fear, and less the feeling of guilt or fear of punishment, the pursuit of freedom, or the rebellion against the power that encounters rejection in many Internet users.
However, it is a proven fact that the search terms are not only stored, but also passed on to third parties in the event of an event, and in these cases there is no protection for the personal rights of the Internet user.
A prime example of this was the recent anti-pedophilia action in Brazil, in the course of which Google provided the Brazilian government with information collected by the community site called "Orkut" and also enabled the identification of the pedophiles.
However, users concerned about personal rights were still able to breathe in in May, when Google, together with the civil rights organization EFF, successfully sued the FBI: accordingly, Google can not be forced in the future to disclose information to the FBI on secret request.
(However, the federal government has successfully obtained the publication of 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms with reference to the Youth Protection Act passed years ago, but it has been retroactively deprived of the list of individual users, or their web and search terms list, for two months.)
Google’s image remains controversial: Those who don’t like to disclose their personal data because they fear the loss of their privacy and privacy through the use of Google services, the company is whipping with the indignation due to the conservative companies.
However, the American “geek culture” present in many countries, uniting enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users, sees the next generation of “cool entrepreneurs” in them, unlike Microsoft, which is the Windows market leader, even though both are fighting for the same goal.
One possible reason for this is that, unlike Microsoft, Google does not ask its users for identification codes and provides its services free of charge, so an open, constantly updated source code and program package appear to be far more attractive, youthful and cooler than the official practices of the software giant.
On the other hand, the geeks see through the problematic relationship between personal rights and the Internet sharply - a relationship that has become the focus in recent years thanks in particular to the term "Web 2.0".
The "Web 2.0" is about nothing more than collaboration, that is, users deliberately leave traces and use the available communication channels, and even if the scales are individually different, the main thing remains the same, namely to show themselves publicly.
An average teenager can manage their profile at the same time on several community portals - from Facebook to Xanga, they can connect them through other services such as Twitter, or music services such as last.fm, and can eventually integrate all of this into a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm.
And a number of other exemplary cases prove: Looking at the party photos last night, the girlfriend soon finds out with whom her unfaithful friend has been pleased, or the employee is fired because in his blog he is only too honest to air his anger about the company management - one thing is certain: the term "private" is new.
Who leads an online life is what he reveals about himself - so in roughly one could formulate the basic idea behind the behavior of today's youth.
And anyone who tries to keep something secret, or even circumvent Google’s monopoly, may like to do so – such as with Scroogle, a tool that, while accessing Google’s search engine, deliberately leaves no trace.
Not a few people do not intentionally register on community pages so that they are not found, but also Google’s online applications, such as text processing and graphics tools and RSS feeds, can handle alternative versions that are not tied to huge server parks and therefore do not generate the best possible profile of the user.
Public opinion, however, is waiting for Google to show its true face.
With its current value of USD 156 billion, the company is even in front of IBM (USD 140 billion), Intel (USD 124 billion) or Coca-Cola (USD 110 billion), the advertising spaces of AdWords/AdSense threaten the revenues of the advertising agencies, and the increasingly imported services not only provide software to others, but also Microsoft.
Critical viewers, however, also find the disturbing counter-polar: For example, the management of the company would have completely rejected a protest of the employees, after the fees of the company's own kindergarten were doubled, in addition, the management thought that the multiple meals of the employees was too expensive.
The internal regulation of the Group is that no new service is advertised in advance, but only if it is already available. However, the events of the coming months and years could again shake a lot: while some believe that Google's book and magazine scanning or archiving project "because of the fact that other companies are now taking on such a large problem"
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database is already supplying the next generation of sci-fi authors with the substance - for example, "Scroogled", the famous novel by Cory Doctorow describes in the best Orwellian way a future in which a person becomes terribly close thanks to Google-related data.
