Intelligent car imitates Hummel’s flight
What would be the best way to develop new accident prevention technologies if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was unveiled, in which Nissan engineers were inspired by Hummeln to create new accident-preventing systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the autorobot-controlled BR23C biomimetic system, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of the bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval “private area” that is very similar to our own “shield,” said Kazuhhiro Doi, Product Manager for Technology PR and Research Development, at the exhibition.
The compound eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
To mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers picked up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180 degree field of view within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is recorded in fractions of a second, and the car robot immediately changes course, similar to the movement of the bees, by turning the tyres at the appropriate angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
"If it were not so, the autorobot could not react quickly enough to evade the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the autorobot project.
The system must respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer that is still considered unavoidable within the accidents at present.
The entire process must reflect the behavior of the bees when they evade other bees.
And that has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, the evasion, unlike the bees, can not take place up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and that is only in the direction of the tyre's swivelability.
While the bees here have infinite possibilities to evade other bees, the researchers could only use the rotational motion of the car robot, i.e. the acceleration and deceleration.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer lifespan than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and react to them accordingly.
It does not need to store these, or produce an intuitive, logical response based on previous maneuvers, so that it continuously takes only a handful of KB of memory.
It does not require gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production as standard within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by consciously guiding the driver around obstacles and thus guiding him to the target.
