Like the Central Statistical Office, domestic sales prices rose by 0.1% in August 2008 compared to the previous month, and compared to August 2007, by 12.9%.
Export prices were 1.1% higher than in July 2008, and fell by 3.9% from the previous year’s prices.
Due to changes in domestic and export prices, production prices were 0.7% higher than in the previous month and 3.2% higher than in 2007.
Domestic sales prices have only slightly increased, i.e. by 0.1 per cent, compared to the previous month.
Also, the selling prices of the manufacturing industry have risen only slightly - 0.1% - since July.
The biggest price increase in August 2008 was for leather goods (2.8 per cent) - mainly for bags and belts - the increase was 4.6 per cent, for shoes the prices went up by 2.5 per cent.
Higher prices for plastics and chemical raw materials significantly boosted prices for chemicals and production (1.6%).
Price declines in crude oil processing (1.4 per cent), electrical and technical equipment (0.9 per cent) and wood processing (0.1 per cent) were slight.
Prices in paper production, publishing and printing remained unchanged.
In other branches of the manufacturing industry, a price increase of between 0.2 and 0.9 percent was measured.
In the major domestic sales markets of the industry, such as electricity, gas, steam and water, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, primarily due to the increase in gas prices introduced on July 1.
Considering the domestic sales markets of the manufacturing industry in the year, prices in crude oil processing have risen the fastest (32.4%).
In the metalworking sector, an increase of 13.2% was observed, while the increase in the manufacture of food, beverages, and tobacco was 11%.
A decline in prices was observed in the textile industry (2.5 percent) and in electrical and technical equipment (0.3 percent).
The extent of the cost increase in the other manufacturing industries was between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing industry climbed by 10.2 percent last year.
Prices for electricity, gas, steam and water increased by 18.7% compared to the previous year.
On the domestic sales market, the highest price increase was recorded in August in the asset sector (0.7 per cent).
In the production sectors for consumer goods, prices rose by 0.3 per cent, while in the energy and processing sector they remained the same compared to the previous month.
The largest price increase in August 2008 was observed in the energy and re-use sector (16.8%) compared to the 2007 comparison period.
In the sectors manufacturing consumer goods, a price increase of 6.8 percent was noted, while in the investment goods, a price decrease of 1.4 percent was noted.
The industry’s export prices measured in Forint rose 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, but declined by 3.9 per cent year-on-year.
