Járóka: The cycle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today, in Paris, the European Summit on Equal Opportunities, which will be hosted this year by the French Presidency of the Council of the European Union, has begun.
In her speech to the plenary, Lívia Járóka, a Fidesz member of the European People’s Party, drew attention, in particular, to educational segregation, as it is one of the most serious violations of the law that affects Roma children, and it is the biggest obstacle to their need for validity.
The high-level conference was opened by the French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, Xavier Bertrand, on behalf of the French Presidency, and Vladimir Spidla, EU Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Among the participants were representatives of governments, the European social partners, as well as the most important European legal and civil organisations in the field of equal opportunities.
As the press office of Fidesz MEPs reports, Járóka has pointed out that in addition to discrimination in job search, Roma would be displaced from the labour market primarily because of their low level of education.
"The vast majority of Roma youth have no secondary education, and thanks to poor primary education, only a small part of them can achieve a higher education degree."
Mr Járóka also stressed that education is a fundamental human right, which plays a key role in asserting other human rights.
Investments in the early education of Roma children could strengthen the economies of the EU Member States.
MEPs believe that it is important that a broader circle of people - i.e. Roma and non-Roma - become aware of these connections.
Because the earlier a Roma student starts school, the greater his chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market; and through income and sales tax, they contribute to national spending.
"As citizens of the Union, Roma must be guaranteed the right to quality education - poor and segregated education must be stopped" - said Lívia Járóka.
As the honourable Member has stated, a common, objective and action-oriented approach by the European Union is necessary in order to speed up the process of desegregation in the education sector, and it is essential for this to comply correctly with the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
"We must break the cycle of poverty, segregation and unemployment and give Roma children the democratic opportunities to contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens," Járóka said.
Since the Congress in Berlin last year, the summit has been held annually with the aim of creating a unique forum for the advancement of the objectives of equality of opportunity and freedom of discrimination at the European level, but also at the national level, in the sense of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities".
