The first of these phenomena is the new discovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state combined with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis means the decline of banking and financial institutions, which have close ties to foreign countries and at the same time manage an enormous amount of the wealth of private households living in a single state.
This represents an immediate political problem for governments: namely, how to behave towards the families concerned, which are also a huge number of voters.
So the crisis appears economically global, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have fallen into disrepair and lost its right to speak: the clear proof of this has been given by the EU, which, due to its division into different national and international conflicts, does not know how to find a common path.
Therefore, everyone is now counting on the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and especially the distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis has become increasingly serious, only the United States in the economic situation can save itself without foreign aid.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus, two prerequisites not to be overestimated – under certain circumstances – that no international organization and no market will otherwise be able to rely on in a similar way.
The new emphasis placed on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that has recently been associated in the economy with a sector closely related to it: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is just now, when we were so convinced that we have long since entered a networked global realm, a realm of ever-differentiated technologies, of the intangible, that we must at once determine how our future will increasingly depend on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
While they can all be transported from one place to another in the world, they are still connected to the extreme by a narrowly defined piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, one who has such a territory is advantageous to another who lives in an unproductive, waterless or oil-free area.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, presupposes a short delay.
Who says territory, who says government, who says politics, says leadership.
