THEME IMMIGRATION: THE NEW YORK TIMES QUESTION: Is ITALY RACIST?
Italy, "the former country of emigrants has recently become one of the preferred countries for immigrants", which are only accepted with opposition.
This is what the New York Times asks in a long article dedicated entirely to the theme of racism in Italy, based on the case of the young, Burkina Faso-born Abdul William Guibre, who was murdered in Milan a month ago after stealing a pack of cookies.
The case testifies to what the Times calls the "Paradox of the North": the northern regions are those where "the most integration and work opportunities" exist, and yet "the highest degree of anti-immigration sentiment and the greatest support of the League of the North is recorded".
As a confirmation of the growing tension between Italians and immigrants, the Times cites further episodes of intolerance from Milan, Rome, Parma, Ciampino and Castel Volturno.
And not just that.
The new legislation introduced by the Lega against immigration and for the faster expulsion of illegal immigrants is also cited as a sign of climate change in Italy.
Giorgio Napolitano asked the Pope at a meeting at the Quirinal for a cooperation between the Church and the State to combat racism.
Students victims of up to 900 euros per room high rental prices
The student housing market is not in crisis.
According to the latest survey by Sunia, the tenant union, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken very serious turns. Entire groups of students are losing their right to study because their families are unable to support them at this level" – says the Sunia leader, Laura Mariani – "in these cities, the high demand on the part of the students has led to a deformation of the market.
In addition, most rental offers involve a number of violations: free contracts, missing registrations, no rental price limit, unauthorized sub-rentals.
For the Sunia, there is a need for extraordinary measures, which will lead to lower rental prices through a revision of taxation.
A closer look at the study shows that in Milan, a sleeping capacity in the Brianza district is needed for around 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Bande Nere district) and ends with 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera districts or even 900 euros in the Vittoria district.
In Florence, a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room 700.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in the neighborhoods around the university, there are 250/280 euros for a bed of necessity, 370 to 500 euros for a single room.
In Rome, the prices in the neighbourhoods around the university are around 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a bed in a double room.
Just a little deeper are the rentals in the neighborhoods around the other universities of Rome: 550 euros in Ostiense and Cinecittà.
Only those who dodge outside districts can save money: 300 euros for a sleeping place and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar neighborhoods.
In Naples you need 300-450 euros for a bed, for a room the price is between 400 and 600 euros in the most expensive neighborhoods, the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari a bed costs 250-350 euros, a single room at least 350.
In the smallest cities, prices are lower, but they have a greater weight in the urban economy.
In cities where the phenomenon of renting to non-European students is more common, such as Perugia, there is even another anomaly: rents that are 25-30% above average are demanded by foreign students.
Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinemas
The historic cinemas close due to the favoured multiplex cinemas.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes.”
This picture by the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the major urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, in the long run means death for the single-room cinema in the center. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also bears the traits of a cultural crime.
Most of the places affected are historical places full of memories, "it's like losing a friend with whom you have traveled a piece of street full of emotions", says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who brought him the Oscar and the Grand Prix of Cannes 20 years ago. It is always the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which is lost to life.
The figures provided by Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the huge number of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these ticks paid for the most of the cinemas in the big cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected are Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy leads the lists, 81 are in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has evolved in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, the president of the Anec, "it is useful that new structures are also emerging, but first of all is the preservation of the already existing, because when a hall in the city closes, not all its regular customers are ready to look for an old multiplex cinema on the peripheral.
And here the lack of state for the fund of the trade union remains an external consideration: the debt burden recorded by the state amounts to about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from an ethical and moral point of view that the government does not comply with existing laws.
To sustain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros per year would be of need".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, because of fears about the old cinema halls, decided to protect it by an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first agreement of its kind in Italy, which aims to protect and support the traditional cinemas as well as the ones in the historical center.
The measures envisaged include tax preferences for cinema operators as well as benefits for the public in terms of local transport: it will be allowed to drive to the traffic-limited areas of the Centre and also to park at cheaper parking fees.
"It is a delightful initiative," said Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will follow our example and also design new concepts.
Of course, we also need better audio and video equipment in order to be able to counteract the superpower of multiplex rooms, because after all, today’s audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of Baghiera’s “Supercinema”, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the “Nuovo cinema Paradiso”, even though I had been playing with the idea for 10 years.
For 25 years I have been living in Rome; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side so as not to have to see the dust-covered posters.
The links between politics and 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to adapt the decisions of the municipality to the interests of the Mafia group Piromalli.
The accusations made by the Calabrian Anti-Mafia Attorney’s Office against Mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of the municipality of Gioia Tauro, who were arrested this morning for involvement in mafia business, are serious.
Also handcuffed was Gioacchino Piromalli, the senior intermediary between the clan and the public administration, as well as his nephew: the lawyer, who bears the same name as the boss of the clan, had already been convicted of involvement in criminal associations of the mafia, at that time for a sum of 10 million euros.
"Disregarding any kind of moral and legal norm," the lawyers write, "the two local administrations had decided to pay the lawyer Piromalli money for consulting activities."
"This has made it possible for the mafia group to officially enter the town halls and determine the policy of the public administration," the judges said.
The president of the Calabrian Regional Committee, Agazio Loiero, does not deny that in his region "it is anything but an exception to encounter links of local administrations and organized crime." "There are places where the concentration of the mafia is greater than in others where such links are virtually inevitable.
But there are also local politicians who resist the pressure of the 'Ndrangheta: heroes who get a white vest."
The arrests of this morning follow those of last July, with which, according to the police of the Clan Piromalli was beheaded.
Since the end of last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved, but already in 1991 – and also at that time due to alleged links between organized crime and local administration – local politicians had been removed from their municipal offices.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, then mayor of the Udc, was elected head of the centre-right coalition in May 2006.
He shouted scandal when the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the municipal council.
He was interested in Deputy Interior Minister Marco Minniti, whom he testified had invented everything for political and strategic reasons, but the judges explained in connection with this morning’s arrest warrant that the Piromalli clan had even dared to apply for a change to the A3 project.
From an eavesdropping action in connection with the investigation into the Dal Torrione case, there has been a willingness to meet the wishes of an entrepreneur who is known to be a representative of the large group around the Piromalli – making the public administration’s actions identical to the interests of this clan.”
When the energy flows from the waves, suddenly the big ones run up.
It is a non-extinguishing source of money that covers over 70% of the planet’s surface and only now do the world’s major energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at, and also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and investigated for 70 years; it is no coincidence that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil broke down around 1980, the idea of marine energy was lost, but now environmental organizations and the rising price of oil are pushing for new impulses in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world’s energy needs could be covered by the energy generated by the ocean waves.
This would be equivalent to twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, the currents and tides.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to now rely on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract in 2005 for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy sector are now focusing on marine energy production.
“Chevron is investigating these technologies,” said a spokesman for a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal, “and is weighing the possibility of working with us.”
This is about acquiring an approval from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially considering that the United States continues to produce oil in Alaska, and President Bush recently set in motion plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; if the details are not known, then observers speak of an increasing interest.
Still technologies worthy of improvement.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still on the rise, not least because the last doubts have not yet been clarified by environmentalists.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland have been rather small in size and do not seem to be causing serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a far greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are several possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected bows.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the bogies up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the float via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned installations of this type, which are only awaiting state approval, and some of the energy generated could also be used for military facilities.
Verdant Power, however, already produces energy for a department store and a parking lot using underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long queue of potential customers is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Power Generation Research, the potential that lies in the tides is of particular interest at the moment.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and also waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is tidal energy that led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to invest $7.5 million in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
